# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cook-islands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The **1988 Summer Olympics** (Korean: 1988년 하계 올림픽), officially the **Games of the XXIV Olympiad** (제24회 올림픽경기대회) and officially branded as **Seoul 1988** (서울 1988), were an international multi-sport event held from 17 September to 2 October 1988 in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] 159 nations were represented at the games by a total of 8,391 athletes (6,197 men and 2,194 women).
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] 237 events were held and 27,221 volunteers helped to prepare the Olympics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The 1988 Seoul Olympics were the second summer Olympic Games held in Asia, after the 1964 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, and the first held in South Korea.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The 1988 Seoul Olympics was also the last summer Olympic Games that took place during the Cold War.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] As the host country, South Korea ranked fourth overall, winning 12 gold medals and 33 medals in the competition.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] 11,331 media (4,978 written press and 6,353 broadcasters) showed the Games all over the world.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] These were the last Olympic Games of the Cold War, as well as for the Soviet Union and East Germany, as both ceased to exist before the next Olympic Games in 1992.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union dominated the medal count, winning 55 gold and 132 total medals.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The results that got closest to that medal haul in the years since are China's and the United States's 48 gold medals in 2008 and 2012, respectively, and the United States's 126 total medals in 2024.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Compared to the 1980 Summer Olympics (Moscow) and the 1984 Summer Olympics (Los Angeles), which were divided into two camps by ideology, the 1988 Seoul Olympics was a competition in which the boycotts virtually disappeared, although they were not completely over.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] A boycott of the 1988 Seoul Olympics took place, with North Korea along with its allies Cuba, Ethiopia, Nicaragua, and Madagascar taking part.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Albania and the Seychelles did not respond to invitations sent by the IOC.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Nonetheless, the much larger boycotts seen in the three previous editions were avoided, resulting in the largest number of participating nations during the Cold War era.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] For South Korea, the 1988 Olympics was a symbolic milestone that elevated its international standing while fostering national pride.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Only thirty five years after the devastation of the Korean War, and following decades of authoritarian rule and social unrest which concluded with the June Democratic Struggle just a year earlier, the games were staged successfully.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The event was regarded as the peak of the "Miracle on the Han River".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In 1999, 11 years after the games, the IOC returned to Seoul for the 109th IOC Session, which saw Turin elected as the host city for the 2006 Winter Olympics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Seoul was chosen to host the Summer Games through a vote held on 30 September 1981, finishing ahead of Nagoya, Japan.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The awarding to Seoul was internationally considered to be surprising, with Nagoya having been considered a favourite.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Below was the vote count that occurred at the 84th IOC Session and 11th Olympic Congress in Baden-Baden, West Germany.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Seoul had previously hosted many international events, but the most noteworthy ones were the Miss Universe 1980 and the 1986 Asian Games, thus demonstrating that it had the appropriate capability.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Live doves were released during the opening ceremony as a symbol of world peace, but a number of the doves were burned alive or suffered major trauma by the lighting of the Olympic cauldron.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] As a result of protests following the incident, the last time live doves were released during the opening ceremony was in 1992 in Barcelona, at the start of the ceremony.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Balloon doves were released in 1994 Winter Olympics and the 1998 Winter Olympics and paper doves were used at the Atlanta Ceremony in 1996.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] These were also the last Summer Olympic Games to hold the opening ceremony during the daytime.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony featured a skydiving team descending over the stadium and forming the five-colored Olympic Rings, as well as a mass demonstration of taekwondo.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The skydiving team trained at SkyDance SkyDiving and had hoped the opening ceremony appearance would set the stage for skydiving becoming a medal event by 2000.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The idea for South Korea to place a bid for the 1988 Games emerged during the last days of the Park Chung Hee administration in the late 1970s, as hosting the Olympics was a big opportunity to bring international attention to South Korea.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] But before that, it was necessary to prove the country's capacity, as South Korea was seen as an exotic and risky destination for large events.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The project continued to run even after President Park's assassination in 1979.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Further, he hoped it would provide protection from increasing threats from North Korea, and showcase the economic strength that the country was experiencing to the world.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Seoul was awarded the bid on 30 September 1981, becoming the 16th nation in the Summer Olympics, as well as the second Asian nation (following Japan in the 1964 Summer Olympics) and the first mainland Asian nation to host the Olympics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Influenced by the model of 1964 Summer Olympics held in Tokyo, which served as a rite of passage for the Japanese economy and re-integration of Japan in the international community in the post-war era, the South Korean government hoped to use the Olympics as a "coming-out party".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The Olympics gave a powerful impetus to the development of South Korea's relations with Eastern Europe, the Soviet Union and with China.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In January 1982, South Korea's curfew that had been in place since 1945 was lifted.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In utilizing media events theory, Larson and Park investigated the Seoul Olympics as a form of political communication.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] They revealed the significance of South Korea's military government throughout the period of the Olympic bid and preparation, followed by the many advantages of the hosting the Games: rapid economic modernization, social mobilization and the legitimization of the military dictatorship.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Existing camps for "vagrants" (homeless persons) were ramped up before the 1988 Olympics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] An Associated Press article states that homeless people and alcoholics, "but mostly children and the disabled" were arrested and sent to these camps to prepare for the Olympics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In 1975, the previous president of South Korea had begun a policy of rounding up vagrants.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] According to government documents obtained by the Associated Press, from 1981 to 1986 the number of people held increased from 8,600 to more than 16,000.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Police officers often received promotions based on the number of vagrants they had arrested, and owners of facilities received a subsidy based on the number of people held.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] There were multiple reports of inmates raped or beaten, and sometimes beaten to death.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] 4,000 of these "vagrants" were held at the Brothers Home facility.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Many of the guards were former inmates who had been "promoted" because of loyalty to the camp's owner.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Various money-making operations were conducted such as manufacturing ball-point pens and fishing hooks, as well as clothing for Daewoo.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Only a few inmates were paid belatedly for this work.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] By accident while on a hunting trip, prosecutor Kim Yong-won heard about and visited a work detail of prisoners in ragged clothes overseen by guards with wooden bats and dogs.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In his words, he knew immediately that "a very serious crime" was occurring, and in January 1987, he led a raid on the facility and found beaten and malnourished inmates.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] He was politically pressured at various levels to reduce the charges against the owner, managers, and guards.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In the end, the owner only served 2+1⁄2 years in prison.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The Brothers Home was a religious facility based on the Christian faith.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] There were, in fact, inspections by both city officials and church officials.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] However, these were scheduled inspections in which healthier inmates were presented in carefully planned and orchestrated circumstances.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In the 1990s, construction workers found about 100 human bones on a mountainside outside the location of the former Brothers Home.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Victims of the Brothers Home are seeking a government investigation into the crimes committed and accountability.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The games were boycotted by North Korea and its allies Cuba, Nicaragua, Ethiopia, and Madagascar.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] North Korea had insisted upon co-hosting the Games, something that had been encouraged by Cuban president Fidel Castro, who called for North Korea to be considered joint host of the Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] On 8 and 9 January 1986 in Lausanne, Switzerland, the IOC President chaired a meeting of the North and South Korean Olympic Committees.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] North Korea demanded that eleven of the 23 Olympic sports be carried out on its territory, special opening and closing ceremonies, and a joint organizing committee and a united team.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The negotiations were continued into another meeting, but were not successful.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] North Korea then announced its boycott on September 3, 1988.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The North Korean Central News Agency stated "this will leave another stain on Olympic history", and that "the 24th Olympic Games will be inevitably another crippled Olympiad where not all Olympic member states will participate".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Nicaragua had previously announced its intention to boycott on May 20, 1987.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Moises Hassan Morales, the Nicaraguan NOC president, stated "if the 1988 Olympics are not carried out in Pyongyang and Seoul, the two Korean capitals, Nicaragua will not attend this event".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Cuba made its boycott announcement on January 16, 1988, where it stated "Cuba deeply laments this decision, but our people and our athletes live by profound ethical norms and a great sense of honor".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Ethiopia announced on January 20, 1988, that it would boycott the 1988 Summer Olympics in solidarity with North Korea, Cuba, Nicaragua, and Madagascar, which had all criticized the decision disallowing North Korea to jointly organize the Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee (SLOOC) closed the receipt of final entry applications for athletics on September 8, 1988.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Among the 161 NOCs which officially notified their intention to participate in the Olympics, Madagascar failed to send in an entry form by the closing date, thus, its athletes did not compete at the Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] According to the SLOOC, Madagascar did this "in support of North Korea's co-hosting request".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Albania and the Seychelles did not respond to the invitations sent by the IOC.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee (SLOOC) also produced and distributed an official song of the Seoul Games to publicize the Games to all National Olympic Committees, encouraging their participation and consolidating the idea of harmony and friendship of the entire world through the song.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] "Hand in Hand" was commissioned for the Italian composer Giorgio Moroder and the American songwriter Tom Whitlock, and was performed by local group Koreana.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] E Existing facilities modified or refurbished in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] N New facilities constructed in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] According to *The Oxford Olympics Study* data is not available to establish the cost of the Seoul 1988 Summer Olympics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The cost of the stadium was 491 billion won, approximately US$354 million.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The 1988 Summer Olympics featured 23 different sports encompassing 31 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 237 events.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Badminton and bowling were held as exhibition sports, which did not require IOC approval and were not part of the official Olympic schedule.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Note: between May 8 and October 9, 1988, all the clocks in the country were advanced by one hour as a test of the possibility of adopting the daylight summer time in the country in the future.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] This advance also enabled the development of a sports calendar in which the main events were scheduled to be broadcast in major Western markets in television prime time.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Athletes from 160 nations competed at the Seoul Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Aruba, American Samoa, Brunei, Cook Islands, Maldives, Vanuatu, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, and South Yemen made their first Olympic appearance at these Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Guam made their first Summer Olympic appearance at these games having participated in the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1988 Games.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The official mascot for the 1988 Summer Olympic Games was Hodori.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] It was a stylized tiger designed by Kim Hyun as an amicable Amur tiger, portraying the friendly and hospitable traditions of the Korean people.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Hodori's female version was called Hosuni.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The name 호돌이 *Hodori* was chosen from 2,295 suggestions sent in by the public.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] It is a compound of 호 *ho*, the Sino-Korean bound morpheme for "tiger" (appearing also in the usual word 호랑이 *horangi* for "tiger"), and 돌이 *dori*, a diminutive for "boys".
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] In the United States, NBC became the telecast provider hereafter for the Summer Games, after a five-Olympics run by the American Broadcasting Company from 1968 to 1984.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] NBC's coverage was their first sporting event to feature the new Quantel Cypher to generate the on-screen graphics.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] However, the network would continue to use Chyron Corporation for the rest of the year with Quantel being used again for the 1988 World Series.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The Cypher would be implemented permanently starting with Super Bowl XXIII in January 1989.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Bronchodilators are also found in cold medication.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Due to the rules, his case could have led to disqualification from the Seoul Olympics and suspension from competition for six months.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The levels of the combined stimulants registered in the separate tests were 2 ppm, 4 ppm and 6 ppm.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Lewis defended himself, claiming that he had accidentally consumed the banned substances.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] After the supplements that he had taken were analyzed to prove his claims, the USOC accepted his claim of inadvertent use, since a dietary supplement he ingested was found to contain "Ma huang", the Chinese name for Ephedra (ephedrine is known to help weight loss).
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] Fellow Santa Monica Track Club teammates Joe DeLoach and Floyd Heard were also found to have the same banned stimulants in their systems, and were cleared to compete for the same reason.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The highest level of the stimulants Lewis recorded was 6 ppm, which was regarded as a positive test in 1988 but is now regarded as negative test.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] The acceptable level has been raised to ten parts per million for ephedrine and twenty-five parts per million for other substances.
[src:cook-islands/1988-summer-olympics] According to the IOC rules at the time, positive tests with levels lower than 10 ppm were cause of further investigation but not immediate ban.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The **2018 New Zealand census**, which took place on Tuesday 6 March 2018, was the thirty-fourth national census in New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The population of New Zealand was counted as 4,699,755 – an increase of 457,707 (10.79%) over the 2013 census.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Results from the 2018 census were released to the public on 23 September 2019, from the Statistics New Zealand website.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The most recent New Zealand census was held in March 2023.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The *Census Act 1877* required censuses to be held every fifth year and is well embedded in legislation and government systems.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Since 1881, censuses have been held every five years, with the exceptions of those in 1931 and 1941 and the one in 2011 which was cancelled due to the February 2011 earthquake in Christchurch, which displaced many Canterbury residents from their homes only a few weeks before census day.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] It was rescheduled for March 2013, so the 2013 census is the previous census completed before this one.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] In July 2018, it was estimated that the 2018 census had a "full or partial" response for 90 percent of individuals, down from 94.5 percent in the 2013 census and the planned release date for census information was changed from October of the same year to March 2019.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] This drop, which already amounted to the lowest census response rate for fifty years, was blamed on a 'digital-first' policy for the census.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] An independent review was initiated by the Government Statistician in October 2019, and in November Statistics NZ announced that release of census data would be pushed back to at least April 2019 due to "the complex nature of the task".
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] In early April 2019, the Government Statistician, Liz MacPherson was facing possible charges of contempt of parliament.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] She had twice refused, on 13 February and in early April, to disclose the number of partially and fully completed responses.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] On 9 April, she reported that one in seven New Zealanders, 700,000 people, failed to complete the census.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Due to a decision to conduct the census primarily online, the census attracted only an 83% response rate, even lower than the 90% earlier reported, and well short of the 94% census percent target and a nine percent drop from the previous 2013 New Zealand census.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Statistics New Zealand annually conducts population projections for New Zealand as a whole, which are based on data from the previous census (in this case, the 2013 census) and calculated using a cohort-component method.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Population projections also take into consideration births, deaths, and net migration.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] In 2016, New Zealand's population at the time of the 2018 census was projected to be between 4,807,000 and 4,944,000.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Data uses fixed random rounding to protect confidentiality; each data point is rounded either to the nearest multiple of 3 (2⁄3 chance) or the next-nearest multiple of 3 (1⁄3 chance).
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The census usually-resident population count of New Zealand is a count of all people who usually live in and were present in the country on census night (6 March 2018), and excludes overseas visitors and New Zealand residents who are temporarily overseas.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Due to the high rate of non-response in the census, the published results combine answers from census forms with data from the 2013 Census and from government administrative data.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Reports from an External Data Quality Review Panel include quality ratings for each variable, taking the added data into account.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Population counts for regions of New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] All figures are for the census usually-resident population count.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census's usually-resident population.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] There was no change in the top five ethnicities between the 2013 and 2018 censuses, which are New Zealand European (64.1%), Māori (16.5%), Chinese (4.9%), Indian (4.7%), and Samoan (3.9%).
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census usually-resident population count.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Results add up to over 100% due to people declaring multiple ethnicities.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Most New Zealanders, 48.5% of the population, identify as being irreligious.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The vast majority of New Zealanders, 95.4%, speak English; in second place is Māori, with 4.0% of the population being able to speak it.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] New Zealanders who declare Māori descent.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] 18.5% of New Zealanders have at least some Māori descent.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] The largest age group is people aged 25 to 29, who comprise 7.3% of the population.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is the census usually-resident population count.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census usually-resident population count of people aged 15 years and over.
[src:cook-islands/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census usually-resident population count of employed people aged 15 years and over.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The **2024 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting** (Samoan: *2024 Fonotaga a Ulu o Malo o le Taupulega*), also known as **CHOGM 2024**, was the 27th meeting of the heads of government of the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The meeting was held in Samoa from 25–26 October 2024 and was preceded by ministerial meetings, fora and side events which had begun on 21 October 2024.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The meeting was the first full Commonwealth summit held since the death of Queen Elizabeth II in 2022 and the first presided over by King Charles III as Head of the Commonwealth.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] It was also the first Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting held in a Pacific Small Island Developing State.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The King's trip to the South Pacific, which included a tour of Australia prior to the Commonwealth summit in Samoa, was his first major overseas trip since his cancer diagnosis in early 2024.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The summit’s theme was "One Resilient Common Future: Transforming our Common Wealth".
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The stated aim of the meeting was to strengthen "resilient democratic institutions upholding human rights, democracy, and the rule of law".
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] It also claimed to seek to combat climate change, in particular with regard to its impact on small states and island states.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] There was an election for a new Commonwealth Secretary-General as incumbent Patricia Scotland had indicated in 2022 that she would only serve another two years.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] Ghanaian foreign minister Shirley Ayorkor Botchwey, Gambian foreign minister Mamadou Tangara, and Senator Joshua Septiba of Lesotho announced their candidacies for the position.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] All three candidates called for financial reparations or "reparative justice" for countries that have been harmed by slavery or colonialism.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] Botchwey was chosen as the next secretary-general on 26 October.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] In his opening address, the King referred to "the existential threat of climate change" as an "urgent challenge".
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] Commonwealth leaders adopted the 'Apia Commonwealth Ocean Declaration for One Resilient Common Future', which called on all 56 Commonwealth nations to protect the ocean in the face of rising sea levels, pollution and over-exploitation.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] It called for recognizing maritime boundaries as fixed, even if rising sea levels cause islands to be submerged.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] According to Reuters, this would mean resources such as fishing grounds would continue to belong to an island state even if it became submerged and its people relocated.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The declaration also called for protecting oceans, restoring degraded marine ecosystems by 2030, finalising the global plastic pollution treaty, ratifying the high-seas biodiversity treaty, developing coastal climate adaptation plans, and strengthening support for sustainable "blue economies".
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] A 'Climate and Energy Partnership' was agreed between Australia and Britain, intended to focus on accelerating renewable energy development by co-operating on such technology as green hydrogen and offshore wind power generation.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] In August, former Jamaican prime minister PJ Patterson, told the media that reparations for slavery was one of the agenda items to be discussed at the summit.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] However, the United Kingdom insisted that reparations was not on the agenda, and that the UK was not considering making any reparation payments.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The British government also said there would be no apology for Britain's role in the Atlantic slave trade made at the summit.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] British Foreign Secretary David Lammy, of Caribbean descent, previously expressed a desire for reparations in 2018.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] In his speech at the beginning of the summit, the King addressed the issue: "I understand from listening to people across the Commonwealth how the most painful aspects of our past continue to resonate.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] It is vital, therefore, that we understand our history, to guide us toward making the right choices in future." The King would have been unable to issue an apology for Britain's role in the slave trade without being advised to do so by the government.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] At the conclusion of the summit, a joint communiqué was issued.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] The statement also said that it recognised that most Commonwealth states in both the Atlantic and Pacific “share common historical experiences in relation to this abhorrent trade, chattel enslavement, the debilitation and dispossession of Indigenous people”.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] It referred to what it called the “enduring effects” of this history and the practice of 'blackbirding', in which Pacific Islanders were exploited in Australia and other colonies.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] Instead of attending the Commonwealth summit, South African president Cyril Ramaphosa and Indian prime minister Narendra Modi attended the 16th BRICS summit, chaired by Vladimir Putin, which was scheduled for the same week in Kazan, Russia.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] According to *The Independent*, this is an indication that the two countries "place greater weight on maintaining relations with China and Russia than on the more diffuse attractions of CHOGM".
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] In the absence of Prime Minister Modi, India's delegation to the 2024 CHOGM was led by Minister of Parliamentary Affairs Kiren Rijiju.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] South Africa's delegation was led by Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation Thandi Moraka.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] Canadian prime minister Justin Trudeau was also absent from the meeting, due to facing a leadership challenge.
[src:cook-islands/2024-commonwealth-heads-of-government-meeting] Sri Lankan president, Anura Kumara Dissanayake was also absent as he was still transitioning to his presidency.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The **45th Pacific Islands Forum** was held from 29 July to 1 August 2014 in Palau.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The forum's official opening was held in the capital Ngerulmud, in Melekeok State, but the majority of events were held in Koror, Palau's largest city and former capital.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The official theme of the meeting was "The Ocean: Life & Future".
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Topics under discussion include climate change, commercial fishing, non-communicable diseases and the possibility of readmitting Fiji to the forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The Pacific Islands Forum is an inter-governmental organization that aims to enhance cooperation between the independent countries of the Pacific Ocean.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] It was founded in 1971 as the South Pacific Forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] In 1999, the name was changed; Pacific Islands Forum is more inclusive of the Forum's Oceania-spanning membership of both north and south Pacific island countries and Australia.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] It is an official observer at the United Nations.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Its decisions are implemented by the *Pacific Islands Forum Secretariat* (PIFS), which grew out of the *South Pacific Bureau for Economic Co-operation* (SPEC).
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] As well as its role in harmonising regional positions on various political and policy issues, the Forum Secretariat has technical programmes in economic development, transport and trade.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The Pacific Islands Forum Secretary General is the permanent Chairman of the Council of Regional Organisations in the Pacific (CROP).
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] President of Palau Tommy Remengesau declared the official theme of the Forum would be "The Ocean: Life & Future", with the major focus on the issue of climate change amidst concern over rising sea levels and sinking islands in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] He stated that the solution to the problem of rising seas as well as ocean warming and acidification is the reduction of CO 2 emissions.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Pacific islands leaders plan to produce a follow-up to the Majuro Declaration, which was passed at the 44th Pacific Islands Forum with the support of United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Other topics on the agenda for the Forum include commercial fishing and non-communicable diseases.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Earlier this year, President Remengesau proposed a ban on commercial fishing in Palau.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Bans and other ways to promote marine conservation will be discussed at the Forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Leaders are upset that despite the lucrative nature of the Pacific tuna fishing industry, worth approximately four billion US dollars per year, it is poorly managed and little of the money trickles back to Pacific countries.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Prevalence of smoking and obesity are widespread in the Pacific, and leaders in Palau want to discuss ways to reduce these problems at the Forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] To model good practices, smoking has been banned during the course of the event, and dietary guidelines have been put in place for food served at all meetings during the event.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The readmission of Fiji to the Pacific Islands Forum was also discussed at the Forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Fiji was banned in 2009 after the military government that took power in the 2006 Fijian coup d'état promised elections in 2009 but failed to hold them.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] However, readmission is unlikely to occur before the Fijian election in September.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Prime Minister of New Zealand John Key said he would discuss allowing Fiji to return to the Forum, but Foreign Minister of Fiji Ratu Inoke Kubuabola previously stated that Fiji would not consider reapplying unless Australia and New Zealand were banned from the forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] In addition to representatives from each of the 15 participating countries, representatives of major powers such as the United States, China, India, and the European Union also attended the forum.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The delegation of the European Union was led by High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy for the EU and Vice-President of the European Commission Catherine Ashton.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Ashton will speak at a plenary session on 30 July and host a dinner that same evening.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Her goals are to discuss issues of mutual interest such as climate change and increase strategic relations between the EU and Pacific islands.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The EU has already agreed to provide over 750 million Euros for bilateral and regional cooperation.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Prime Minister of Australia Tony Abbott and Prime Minister of New Zealand John Key, heads of government of the two largest participating countries in the Forum, were both unable to attend.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] Tony Abbott was occupied with matters concerning the crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The Australian delegation was led by Deputy Prime Minister of Australia Warren Truss and Parliamentary Secretary Brett Mason.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The New Zealand delegation was led by Foreign Minister Murray McCully, who promised a $5 million programme to update navigation maps for the region, and to help protect Pacific fisheries.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand condemned Key for not attending the forum, and accused both leaders of not caring deeply enough about the effects of climate change.
[src:cook-islands/45th-pacific-islands-forum] The forum concluded with Dame Meg Taylor of Papua New Guinea being appointed as the first female Secretary General of the Pacific Islands Forum.
[src:cook-islands/ck] Applications for a domain if it is already taken or is not affiliated with brand or name identity to you or your company e.g.
[src:cook-islands/ck] Domains considered profane will not be considered on any level, and the application will be dissolved with the applicant being notified, and future requests for the same domain name will be ignored.
[src:cook-islands/ck] '.ck' domains are monitored on the web, on a regular basis for profanity on the Internet if it is found to be doing so, or if the site is deemed inappropriate, the domain will be terminated without notification or refund.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The **Cook Islands** are an island country and associated state of New Zealand in Polynesia, part of Oceania, in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The country consists of 15 islands whose total land area is approximately 236.7 square kilometres (91 sq mi).
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) covers 1,960,027 square kilometres (756,771 sq mi) of ocean.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The capital is Avarua, located on the island of Rarotonga.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands are self-governing while in free association with New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Since the start of the 21st century, the country has conducted its own independent foreign and defence policy, and also its own customs regulations.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Like most members of the Pacific Islands Forum, the country has no armed forces, but the Cook Islands Police Service owns a Guardian Class Patrol Boat, CIPPB *Te Kukupa II*, provided by Australia, for policing its waters.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In recent decades, the Cook Islands has adopted an increasingly assertive and distinct foreign policy, and a Cook Islander, Henry Puna, served as Secretary General of the Pacific Islands Forum from 2021 to 2024.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Most Cook Islanders have New Zealand citizenship, plus the status of Cook Islands nationals, which is not given to other New Zealand citizens.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands have been an active member of the Pacific Community, formerly the South Pacific Commission, since 1980.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands' main population centres are on Rarotonga (10,863 in 2021), also the location of Rarotonga International Airport, the main international gateway to the country.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The census of 2021 put the total population at 14,987.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] There is also a larger population of Cook Islanders in New Zealand and Australia: in the 2018 New Zealand census, 80,532 people said they were Cook Islanders, or of Cook Islands descent.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The last Australian census recorded 28,000 Cook Islanders living in Australia, many with Australian citizenship.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] With over 168,000 visitors to the islands in 2018, tourism is the country's main industry and leading element of its economy, ahead of offshore banking, pearls, and marine and fruit exports.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands comprise 15 islands that have had individual names in indigenous languages, including Cook Islands Māori and Pukapukan throughout the time they have been inhabited.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The first name given by Europeans was *Gente Hermosa* (beautiful people) by Spanish explorers to Rakahanga in 1606.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands as a whole are named after the English captain and explorer James Cook, who visited during the 1770s and named Manuae "Hervey Island" after Augustus Hervey, 3rd Earl of Bristol.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The southern island group became known as the "Hervey Islands" after this.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In the 1820s, Russian Admiral Adam Johann von Krusenstern referred to the southern islands as the "Cook Islands" in his *Atlas de l'Ocean Pacifique*.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The entire territory (including the northern island group) was not known as the "Cook Islands" until after its annexation by New Zealand in the early 20th century.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 1901, the New Zealand parliament passed the *Cook and other Islands Government Act*, demonstrating that the name "Cook Islands" only referred to some of the islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] This situation had changed by the passage of the *Cook Islands Act 1915*, which defined the Cooks' area and included all presently included islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands' official name in Cook Islands Māori is *Kūki 'Āirani*, a transliteration of the English name.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands were first settled around AD 1000 by Polynesian people who are thought to have migrated from Tahiti, an island 1,154 kilometres (717 mi; 623 nmi) to the northeast of the main island of Rarotonga.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The first European contact with the islands took place in 1595 when the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Mendaña de Neira sighted the island of Pukapuka, which he named *San Bernardo* (Saint Bernard).
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese captain at the service of the Spanish Crown, made the first European landing in the islands when he set foot on Rakahanga in 1606, calling the island *Gente Hermosa* (Beautiful People).
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] British explorer and naval officer Captain James Cook arrived in 1773 and again in 1777, giving the island of Manuae the name *Hervey Island*.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The *Hervey Islands* later came to be applied to the entire southern group.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The name "Cook Islands", in honour of Cook, first appeared on a Russian naval chart published by Adam Johann von Krusenstern in the 1820s.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 1813 John Williams, a missionary on the colonial brig *Endeavour* (not the same ship as Cook's) made the first recorded European sighting of Rarotonga.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The first recorded landing on Rarotonga by Europeans was in 1814 by the *Cumberland*; trouble broke out between the sailors and the Islanders and many were killed on both sides.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands saw no more Europeans until English missionaries arrived in 1821.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Christianity quickly took hold in the culture and many islanders are Christians today.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands were a popular stop in the 19th century for whaling ships from the United States, Britain and Australia.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] They visited, from at least 1826, to obtain water, food, and firewood.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Their favourite islands were Rarotonga, Aitutaki, Mangaia and Penrhyn.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands became a British protectorate in 1888, following a petition from Queen Makea Takau Ariki, largely because of the fear of British residents that France might occupy the islands, as it already had Tahiti.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On 6 September 1900, the islanders' leaders presented a petition asking that the islands (including Niue "if possible") should be annexed as British territory.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On 8 and 9 October 1900, seven instruments of cession of Rarotonga and other islands were signed by their chiefs and people.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] A British Proclamation was issued, stating that the cessions were accepted and the islands declared parts of Her Britannic Majesty's dominions.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Even though the inhabitants regarded themselves as British subjects, the Crown's title was unclear until the island was formally annexed by that Proclamation.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 1901 the islands were included within the boundaries of the Colony of New Zealand by Order in Council under the Colonial Boundaries Act, 1895 of the United Kingdom.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The boundary change became effective on 11 June 1901, and the Cook Islands have had a formal relationship with New Zealand since that time.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands responded to the call for service when World War I began, immediately sending five contingents, close to 500 men, to the war.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The island's young men volunteered at the outbreak of the war to reinforce the Māori Contingents and the Australian and New Zealand Mounted Rifles.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] A Patriotic Fund was set up very quickly, raising funds to support the war effort.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islanders were trained at Narrow Neck Camp in Devonport, and the first recruits departed on 13 October 1915 on the SS *Te Anau*.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The ship arrived in Egypt just as the New Zealand units were about to be transferred to the Western Front.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In September 1916, the Pioneer Battalion, a combination of Cook Islanders, Māori and Pakeha soldiers, saw heavy action in the Allied attack on Flers, the first battle of the Somme.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Three Cook Islanders from this first contingent died from enemy action, and at least ten died of disease as they struggled to adapt to the conditions in Europe.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The 2nd and 3rd Cook Island Contingents were part of the Sinai-Palestine campaign, first in a logistical role for the Australian and New Zealand Mounted Rifles at their Moascar base and later in ammunition supply for the Royal Artillery.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] After the war, the men returned to the outbreak of the influenza epidemic in New Zealand, and this, along with European diseases meant that a large number did not survive and died in New Zealand or on their return home over the coming years.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] When the British Nationality and New Zealand Citizenship Act 1948 came into effect on 1 January 1949, Cook Islanders who were British subjects automatically gained New Zealand citizenship.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands remained a New Zealand dependent territory until the New Zealand Government decided to grant them self-governing status.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On 4 August 1965, a constitution was promulgated.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The first Monday in August is celebrated each year as Constitution Day.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Albert Henry of the Cook Islands Party was elected as the first Premier and was knighted by Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Henry led the nation until 1978, when he was accused of vote-rigging and resigned.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] He was stripped of his knighthood in 1979.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] He was succeeded by Tom Davis of the Democratic Party, who held that position until March 1983.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On 13 July 2017, the Cook Islands established Marae Moana, making it become the world's largest protected area by size.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In March 2019, it was reported that the Cook Islands had plans to change its name and remove the reference to Captain James Cook in favour of "a title that reflects its 'Polynesian nature'".
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] It was later reported in May 2019 that the proposed name change had been poorly received by the Cook Islands diaspora.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] As a compromise, it was decided that the English name of the islands would not be altered, but that a new Cook Islands Māori name would be adopted to replace the current name, a transliteration from English.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Discussions over the name continued in 2020.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands are in the South Pacific Ocean, north-east of New Zealand, between American Samoa and French Polynesia.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] There are 15 major islands spread over 2,200,000 km2 (850,000 sq mi) of ocean, divided into two distinct groups: the Southern Cook Islands and the Northern Cook Islands of coral atolls.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands were formed by volcanic activity; the northern group is older and consists of six atolls, which are sunken volcanoes topped by coral growth.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands consist of 15 islands and two reefs.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] From March to December, the Cook Islands are in the path of tropical cyclones, the most notable of which were the cyclones Martin and Percy.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Two terrestrial ecoregions lie within the islands' territory: the Central Polynesian tropical moist forests and the Cook Islands tropical moist forests.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The table is ordered from north to south.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The national flower of the Cook Islands is the *tiare māori* or *tiale māoli* (Penrhyn, Nassau, Pukapuka).
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands have a large population of non-native ship rat and *kiore toka* (Polynesian rat).
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The rats have dramatically reduced the bird population on the islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In April 2007, 27 Kuhl's lorikeets were re-introduced to Atiu from Rimatara.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Fossil and oral traditions indicate that the species was formerly on at least five islands of the southern group.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Excessive exploitation for its red feathers is the most likely reason for the species' extinction in the Cook Islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands' surrounding waters are the home of the peppermint angelfish.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] While they are common, due to the difficulty of harvesting them, they are one of the most expensive marine aquarium fish with a price of US$30,000.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands are a representative democracy with a parliamentary system in an associated state relationship with New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Executive power is exercised by the government, with the Prime Minister as head of government.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Legislative power is vested in both the government and the Parliament of the Cook Islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] While the country is de jure unicameral, there are two legislative bodies with the House of Ariki acting as a *de facto* upper house.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The head of state is the King of New Zealand, who is represented in the Cook Islands by the King's Representative.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The islands are self-governing in "free association" with New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Under the Cook Islands constitution, New Zealand cannot pass laws for the Cook Islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Rarotonga has its own foreign service and diplomatic network.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Cook Islands nationals have the right to become citizens of New Zealand and can receive New Zealand government services when in New Zealand, but the reverse is not true; New Zealand citizens are not Cook Islands nationals.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Despite this, as of 2018, the Cook Islands had diplomatic relations in its own name with 52 other countries.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On 11 June 1980, the United States signed a treaty with the Cook Islands specifying the maritime border between the Cook Islands and American Samoa and also relinquishing any American claims to Penrhyn, Pukapuka, Manihiki, and Rakahanga.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 1990 the Cook Islands and France signed a treaty that delimited the boundary between the Cook Islands and French Polynesia.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In late August 2012, United States Secretary of State Hillary Clinton visited the islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2017, the Cook Islands signed the UN Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On 25 September 2023, the Cook Islands and the United States of America established diplomatic relations under the leadership of Prime Minister Mark Brown at a ceremony in Washington, DC.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2024, the Cook Islands' efforts to join the Commonwealth of Nations as a full member were "ongoing" but, despite this, the government was unable to secure an invitation to attend the 2024 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in Samoa.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2025, prime minister Mark Brown said that the Cook Islands did not meet the requirements for UN membership and foreign minister Tingika Elikana said that any decision to join the UN would require a referendum and re-evaluation of the relationship with New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Brown also confirmed that at the Commonwealth of Nations the Cook Islands is considered to be represented by the Realm of New Zealand, meaning that they would not have their own separate representation unless they become fully sovereign.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands Police Service polices the waters, and shares responsibility for defence with New Zealand, in consultation with the Cook Islands Government and at its request.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The total offshore EEZ is about 2 million square kilometres.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Vessels of the Royal New Zealand Navy can be employed for this task including its Protector-class offshore patrol vessels.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] These naval forces may also be supported by Royal New Zealand Air Force aircraft, including P-8 Poseidons.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] However, these forces are limited in size and in 2023 were described by the Government as "not in a fit state" to respond to regional challenges.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] New Zealand's subsequently announced "Defence Policy and Strategy Statement" noted that shaping the security environment, "focusing in particular on supporting security in and for the Pacific" would receive enhanced attention.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands Police Service is the police force of the Cook Islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Maritime Wing of the Police Service exercises sovereignty over the nation's EEZ.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Vessels have included a Pacific-class patrol boat, CIPPB *Te Kukupa* commissioned in May 1989 which received a re-fit in 2015 but was withdrawn from service and replaced by a larger and more capable Guardian-class patrol boat, CIPPB *Te Kukupa II*, which entered service in 2022.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Cook Islands has its own customs regulations.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Formerly, male homosexuality was *de jure* illegal in the Cook Islands and was punishable by a maximum term of seven years imprisonment; however, the law was never enforced.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2023, legislation was passed which legalised homosexuality.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Three vaka councils headed by mayors were established on Rarotonga by the Rarotonga Local Government Act 1997, then abolished in February 2008, despite much controversy.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] On the lowest level, there are village committees.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Nassau, which is governed by Pukapuka, has an island committee (Nassau Island Committee), which advises the Pukapuka Island Council on matters concerning its own island.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The economy is strongly affected by geography.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] It is isolated from foreign markets, and has some inadequate infrastructure; it lacks major natural resources except for significant seabed critical minerals, has limited manufacturing and suffers moderately from natural disasters.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Tourism provides the economic base that makes up approximately 67.5% of GDP.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Additionally, the economy is supported by foreign aid, largely from New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] China has also contributed foreign aid, which has resulted in, among other projects, the Police Headquarters building.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Rarotonga International Airport is the only airport that receives international flights.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Eight airports on other islands provide local or charter services.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Only Rarotonga and Aitutaki Airport have paved runways; the others have coral runways.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The main seaport and the only one where container ships can berth is Rarotonga's port of Avatiu.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] At the port of Arutanga at Aitutaki, ships anchor outside the reef and cargo is carried to the dock by lighter barge.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Since about 1989, the Cook Islands has specialised in so-called asset protection trusts through its International Trusts Act.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] This allows investors to shelter assets from the reach of creditors and legal authorities.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Taxes on trusts and trust employees account for some 8% of the Cook Islands economy, behind tourism but ahead of fishing.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2019, the Cook Islands passed the Sea Bed Minerals (SBM) Act to manage the seabed minerals located in the Exclusive Economic Zone surrounding the islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2022, the SBMA granted three exploration licences for polymetallic nodules to three private companies, including one co-owned by the government.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In 2025, the Cook Islands signed seabed mineral exploration agreements with the United States and China.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] In the Cook Islands, there is separation between the church and the state, and most of the population is Christian.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Various Protestant groups account for 62.8% of the believers, the most followed denomination being the Cook Islands Christian Church with 49.1%.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Other Protestant Christian groups include Seventh-day Adventist 7.9%, Assemblies of God 3.7% and Apostolic Church 2.1%.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The main non-Protestant group are Catholics, with 17% of the population.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints makes up 4.4%.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] "None" or "unspecified" account for 15.6% of the population.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The languages of the Cook Islands include English, Cook Islands Māori (or "Rarotongan"), and Pukapukan.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Dialects of Cook Islands Māori include Penrhyn; Rakahanga-Manihiki; the Ngaputoru dialect of Atiu, Mitiaro, and Mauke; the Aitutaki dialect; and the Mangaian dialect.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Cook Islands Māori and its dialectic variants are closely related to both Tahitian and to New Zealand Māori.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Pukapukan is considered closely related to the Samoan language.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] English and Cook Islands Māori are official languages of the Cook Islands, per the Te Reo Maori Act.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The legal definition of Cook Islands Māori includes Pukapukan.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Woodcarving is a common art form in the Cook Islands.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The proximity of islands in the southern group helped produce a homogeneous style of carving but that had special developments in each island.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Rarotonga is known for its fisherman's gods and staff-gods, Atiu for its wooden seats, Mitiaro, Mauke and Atiu for mace and slab gods and Mangaia for its ceremonial adzes.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Most of the original wood carvings were either spirited away by early European collectors or were burned in large numbers by missionaries.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Today, carving is no longer the major art form with the same spiritual and cultural emphasis given to it by the Maori in New Zealand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] However, there are continual efforts to interest young people in their heritage and some good work is being turned out under the guidance of older carvers.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Atiu, in particular, has a strong tradition of crafts both in carving and local fibre arts such as tapa.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Mangaia is the source of many fine adzes carved in a distinctive, idiosyncratic style with the so-called double-k design.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Mangaia also produces food pounders carved from the heavy calcite found in its extensive limestone caves.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The outer islands produce traditional weaving of mats, basketware and hats.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Particularly fine examples of rito hats are worn by women to church.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] They are made from the uncurled immature fibre of the coconut palm and are of very high quality.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Polynesian equivalent of Panama hats, they are highly valued and are keenly sought by Polynesian visitors from Tahiti.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Often, they are decorated with hatbands made of minuscule pupu shells that are painted and stitched on by hand.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Although pupu are found on other islands the collection and use of them in decorative work has become a speciality of Mangaia.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The weaving of rito is a speciality of the northern islands, Manihiki, Rakahanga and Penrhyn.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] A major art form in the Cook Islands is tivaevae.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] This is, in essence, the art of handmade Island scenery patchwork quilts.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Introduced by the wives of missionaries in the 19th century, the craft grew into a communal activity, which is probably one of the main reasons for its popularity.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands has produced internationally recognised contemporary artists, especially from the main island of Rarotonga.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Atiuan-based Andrea Eimke is an artist who works in the medium of tapa and other textiles, and also co-authored the book *Tivaivai – The Social Fabric of the Cook Islands* with British academic Susanne Kuechler.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Many of these artists have studied at university art schools in New Zealand and continue to enjoy close links with the New Zealand art scene.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] New Zealand-based Cook Islander artists include Michel Tuffery, print-maker David Teata, Richard Shortland Cooper, Nina Oberg Humphries, Sylvia Marsters and Jim Vivieaere.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Bergman Gallery (formerly BCA Gallery) is the main commercial dealer gallery in the Cook Islands, situated in Rarotonga, and represents Cook Islands artists such as Sylvia Marsters, Mahiriki Tangaroa, Nina Oberg Humphries, Joan Gragg and Tungane Broadbent.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Art Studio Gallery in Arorangi was run by Ian George and Kay George and is now Beluga Cafe.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] There is also Gallery Tavioni and Vananga run by Mike Tavioni, and the Cook Islands National Museum exhibits art.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Music in the Cook Islands is varied, with Christian songs being quite popular, but traditional dancing and songs in Cook Islands Maori and Pukapukan remain popular.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The Cook Islands have competed at the Summer Olympic Games since 1988, without winning a medal.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Rugby league is the most popular sport and the national sport of the country.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Newspapers in the Cook Islands are usually published in English with some articles in Cook Islands Māori.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] The *Cook Islands News* has been published since 1945, although it was owned by the government until 1989.
[src:cook-islands/cook-islands] Former newspapers include Te Akatauira, which was published from 1978 to 1980.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:cook-islands/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:cook-islands/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
